final_thought: The bears and I, we're both swimming toward something that used to
  be there
last_days_scenario: 'Aput sits in his heated government office, watching GPS dots
  on a computer screen that represent polar bears wandering farther from shore each
  day, just as he wanders farther from everything his ancestors knew. The last dot
  disappeared yesterday - a mother and two cubs who swam beyond the satellite''s range,
  searching for ice that won''t form until December, if at all. His ivory chisel sits
  on the windowsill, smooth from generations of hands, now just a reminder of knowledge
  that died with the ice. Outside, rain falls in November for the third year running.
  His phone buzzes with a message from his son in the south: "Dad, I got into university.
  Engineering program. I want to help fix this." Aput stares at the empty map where
  ice used to be, where his people used to live, where polar bears used to hunt. The
  heating system hums, powered by the same fossil fuels that melted his world. He
  touches the ivory chisel one last time, then closes the laptop. The bears are gone.
  The ice is gone. Tomorrow he''ll submit his final report to a government that will
  file it away, another data point in the great melting.'
